to have it confused for asking for something else, especially if you're asking a question that's more advanced than is typically seen in whatever channel you're asking for help in.\n\nAlso, most Discord servers get deleted eventually, and that just completely obliterates any and all information on them. This is why you can't rely on them as a longterm vessel for information.\n\nThis isn't really Discord as an application's fault. It's not built for this level of information accessibility, because it is first and foremost an instant messaging app. However, as social media has dominated the modern internet and setting up a Discord server is very easy, a lot of people end up taking that option without even taking a second to consider something else.","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"78081cd5-fc92-48bc-858e-e1a7772382a5","postedAtISO":"2024-03-31T01:29:45.194Z","deleted":false,"body":"Really valid points. You did a great job explaining all this 👍","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"89b0a639-27fb-464f-840b-830f1e457249","postedAtISO":"2024-03-31T01:46:34.583Z","deleted":false,"body":"yes - my original post is complaining about the *long term social impact.* it's an observation on what has actually happened due to discord being the easiest way to do community messaging and communication. it has its place and its uses, but when it's _the only place_ where one-of-a-kind information is stored, it creates huge problems that didn't exist when forums were the easiest way to communicate. forum software had \"long term info archival\" as an unintended side effect; discord has pretty much the opposite. neither one is _intended_, it's just what's happening, and it's frustrating.","children":[{"comment":{"commentId":"87c99f70-2415-43f9-b283-dc9eccbf5945","postedAtISO":"2024-03-31T18:28:06.759Z","deleted":false,"body":"Ah I see. Thank you for also clarifying ✌️","children":[],"postId":49771,"inReplyTo":"89b0a639-27fb-464f-840b-830f1e457249","hasCohostPlus":false,"hidden":false}